TC-01: Hash Length & Encoding Identification (FILE INPUT)
Command
Bash
Copy code
awk '{ print length($0) }' hash.txt
â¡ï¸ Outputs length of each hash.
Encoding check
Bash
Copy code
grep -Eq '^[a-fA-F0-9]+$' hash.txt && echo "HEX"
Bash
Copy code
base64 -d hash.txt >/dev/null 2>&1 && echo "BASE64"
TC-02: Hash Format Signature Detection (FILE INPUT)
Tool: hashid
Bash
Copy code
hashid hash.txt
Bash
Copy code
hashid -m hash.txt
Tool: hash-identifier
Bash
Copy code
hash-identifier
Paste hash from hash.txt when prompted.
TC-03: Determinism / Salt Detection (FILE INPUT)
âš ï¸ Only possible if you can regenerate hashes
Compare two hashes from file:
Bash
Copy code
uniq hash.txt
Multiple identical hashes â†’ unsalted
All unique â†’ possibly salted
TC-04: Entropy & Randomness Test (FILE INPUT)
Convert HEX hashes to binary
Bash
Copy code
cat hash.txt | tr -d '\n' | xxd -r -p > hash.bin
Run entropy test
Bash
Copy code
ent hash.bin
TC-05: Character Frequency Distribution (FILE INPUT)
Bash
Copy code
cat hash.txt | fold -w1 | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr
TC-06: Avalanche Effect Test (FILE INPUT)
âš ï¸ Requires paired hashes of similar inputs.
Example:
Bash
Copy code
xxd -b <(sed -n '1p' hash.txt) > h1.bin
xxd -b <(sed -n '2p' hash.txt) > h2.bin
cmp h1.bin h2.bin
TC-07: Collision Heuristic (FILE INPUT)
Detect duplicates
Bash
Copy code
sort hash.txt | uniq -d
â¡ï¸ Any output = collision or identical input
TC-08: Length Extension Test (FILE INPUT)
âš ï¸ Only applies if:
Hash is MD5 / SHA-1 / SHA-256
You know original message length
Command
Bash
Copy code
./hash_extender \
  --signature $(sed -n '1p' hash.txt) \
  --data test \
  --append extra \
  --format sha256
TC-09: Known Collision Validation (FILE INPUT)
Only valid if algorithm identified as MD5.
Bash
Copy code
md5sum file1 file2
Compare output with hashes in hash.txt.
TC-10: Risk Classification (FILE INPUT)
Check bit length
Bash
Copy code
awk '{ print length($0) * 4 " bits" }' hash.txt
Common Mistakes (Important)
âŒ Running entropy on single hash
âŒ Assuming randomness = security
âŒ Mixing salted and unsalted hashes
âŒ Treating unknown algorithm as acceptable
